






#lg A	kirugu


@(1-2=c223.A.1) To overturn the appointed times, to obliterate the divine plans, the storms gather to strike like a flood.

@(3-11=c223.A.3) @wDN{An}, @wDN{Enlil}, @wDN{Enki} and
{@wDN{Ninḫursaŋa}
} 
{@noteanchor{2 mss. have instead:} @wDN{Ninmaḫ}
}  have decided its fate -- to overturn the divine powers of @wGN{Sumer}, to lock up the favourable reign in its home, to destroy the city, to destroy the house, to destroy the cattle-pen, to level the sheepfold; that the cattle should not stand in the pen, that the sheep should not multiply in the fold, that watercourses should carry brackish water, that weeds should grow in the fertile fields, that mourning plants should grow in the open country,


@(12-21=c223.A.12) that the mother should not seek out her child, that the father should not say @q[father,wife]{“O my dear wife!”, that the junior wife should take no joy in his embrace, that the young child should not grow vigorous on his knee, that the wet-nurse should not sing lullabies; to change the location of kingship, to defile the seeking of oracles, to take kingship away from the Land, to cast the eye of the storm on all the land, to obliterate the divine plans by the order of @wDN{An} and @wDN{Enlil};

@(22-26=c223.A.22) after @wDN{An} had frowned upon all the lands, after @wDN{Enlil} had looked favourably on an enemy land, after @wDN{Nintur} had scattered the creatures that she had created, after @wDN{Enki} had altered the course of the @wWN{Tigris} and @wWN{Euphrates}, after @wDN{Utu} had cast his curse on the roads and highways;

@(27-37=c223.A.27) so as to obliterate the divine powers of @wGN{Sumer}, to change its preordained plans, to alienate the divine powers of the reign of kingship of @wSN{Urim}, to humiliate the princely son in his house @wTN{E-kiš-nu-ŋal}, to break up the unity of the people of @wDN{Nanna}, numerous as ewes; to change the food offerings of @wSN{Urim}, the shrine of magnificent food offerings; that its people should no longer dwell in their quarters, that they should be given over to live in an inimical place; that @wGN{Šimaški} and @wGN{Elam}, the enemy, should dwell in their place; that its shepherd, in his own palace, should be captured by the enemy, that @wRN{Ibbi-@wDN{Suen}} should be taken to the land @wGN{Elam} in fetters, that from Mount @wGN{Zabu} on the edge of the sea to the borders of @wGN{Anšan}, like a swallow that has flown from its house, he should never return to his city;

@(38-46=c223.A.38) that on the two parallel banks of the @wWN{Tigris} and of the @wWN{Euphrates} bad weeds should grow, that no one should set out on the road, that no one should seek out the highway, that the city and its settled surroundings should be razed to ruin-mounds; that its numerous black-headed people should be slaughtered; that the hoe should not attack the fertile fields, that seed should not be planted in the ground, that the melody of the cowherds' songs should not resound in the open country, that butter and cheese should not be made in the cattle-pen, that dung should not be stacked on the ground, that the shepherd should not enclose the sacred sheepfold with a fence, that the song of the churning should not resound in the sheepfold;

@(47-55=c223.A.47) to decimate the animals of the open country, to finish off all living things, that the four-legged creatures of @wDN{Šakkan} should lay no more dung on the ground, that the marshes should be so dry as to be full of cracks and have no new seed, that sickly-headed reeds should grow in the reedbeds and come to an end in a stinking morass, that there should be no new growth in the orchards, that it should all collapse by itself -- so as quickly to subdue @wSN{Urim} like a roped ox, to bow its neck to the ground: the great charging wild bull, confident in its own strength, the primeval city of lordship and kingship, built on sacred ground.

@(56-57=c223.A.56) Its fate cannot be changed. Who can overturn it? It is the command of @wDN{An} and @wDN{Enlil}. Who can oppose it?

@(58-68=c223.A.58) @wDN{An} frightened the very dwellings of @wGN{Sumer}, the people were afraid. @wDN{Enlil} blew an evil storm, silence lay upon the city. @wDN{Nintur} bolted the door of the storehouses of the Land. @wDN{Enki} blocked the water in the @wWN{Tigris} and the @wWN{Euphrates}. @wDN{Utu} took away the pronouncement of equity and justice. @wDN{Inana} handed over victory in strife and battle to a rebellious land. @wDN{Ninŋirsu} poured @wGN{Sumer} away like milk to the dogs. Turmoil descended upon the Land, something that no one had ever known, something unseen, which had no name, something that could not be fathomed. The lands were confused in their fear. The god of the city turned away, its shepherd vanished.

@(69-78=c223.A.69) The people, in their fear, breathed only with difficulty. The storm immobilised them, the storm did not let them return. There was no return for them, the storm did not retreat. This is what @wDN{Enlil}, the shepherd of the black-headed people, did: Enlil, to destroy the loyal households, to decimate the loyal men, to put the evil eye on the sons of the loyal men, on the first-born, @wDN{Enlil} then sent down @wGN{Gutium} from the mountains. Their advance was as the flood of @wDN{Enlil} that cannot be withstood. The great wind of the countryside filled the countryside, it advanced before them. The extensive countryside was destroyed, no one moved about there.

@(79-92=c223.A.79) The dark time was roasted by hailstones and flames. The bright time was wiped out by a shadow.
{@noteanchor{2 mss. add 2 lines:} In the darkness, noses were heaped up, heads were smashed. The storm was a harrow coming from above, the city was struck by a hoe.
}  On that day, heaven rumbled, the earth trembled, the storm worked without respite. Heaven was darkened, it was covered by a shadow; the mountains roared. @wDN{Utu} lay down at the horizon, dust passed over the mountains. @wDN{Nanna} lay at the zenith, the people were afraid. The city's god left his dwelling and stood aside. The foreigners in the city even chased away its dead. Large trees were uprooted, the forest growth was ripped out. The orchards were stripped of their fruit, they were cleaned of their offshoots. The crop drowned while it was still on the stalk, the yield of the grain diminished.
$ (3 lines fragmentary)

@(93-103=c223.A.93) They piled …… up in heaps, they spread …… out like sheaves. There were corpses floating in the @wWN{Euphrates}, weapons smashed heads. The father turned away from his wife saying @q[father,wife]{“This is not my wife!” The mother turned away from her child saying @q[mother,child]{“This is not my child!” He who had a productive estate neglected his estate saying @q[,]{“This is not my estate!” The rich man took an unfamiliar path away from his possessions. In those days the kingship of the Land was defiled. The tiara and crown that had been on the king's head were both spoiled. The lands that had followed the same path were split into disunity. The food offerings of @wSN{Urim}, the shrine of magnificent food offerings, were changed for the worse. @wDN{Nanna} traded away his people, numerous as ewes.

@(104-111=c223.A.104) Its king sat immobilised in his own palace. @wRN{Ibbi-@wDN{Suen}} was sitting in anguish in his own palace. In @wTN{E-namtila}, his place of delight, he wept bitterly. The flood dashing a hoe on the ground was levelling everything. Like a great storm it roared over the earth -- who could escape it? -- to destroy the city, to destroy the house, so that traitors would lie on top of loyal men and the blood of traitors flow upon loyal men.

